## 5. Results

The results show that the Felzenszwalb algorithm effectively partitions natural images into visually meaningful regions. Smaller scale values produce finer segmentation, while larger scale values result in fewer and larger regions.

The method preserves important boundaries and performs well on natural images with varying textures and colors.

---

## 6. Discussion

### Strengths
- Computationally efficient  
- Produces coherent and meaningful segments  
- Suitable for large natural images  

### Limitations
- Sensitive to parameter tuning  
- Over-segmentation may occur in highly textured regions  
- Does not provide semantic interpretation  

### Real-World Applications
- Object detection preprocessing  
- Medical image analysis  
- Image compression  
- Scene understanding  

---

## 7. Conclusion

This project implemented graph-based image segmentation using the Felzenszwalb algorithm. The method efficiently segments natural images while preserving essential boundary information.

Despite its sensitivity to parameter selection, the algorithm remains a powerful and scalable segmentation approach. Future work may integrate this method with machine learning techniques for higher-level semantic understanding.
